0e969447-37e3-4232-a012-c4e7fe7b1ea4.1c5667b0-9f91-4c4c-8d8b-68e6796a05ca.description=
Allows a user to select how they should be notified of the outcome of a flow, and shows them a message in that way.

Inputs\:
notifyData -  The text of the notification message.
notifyMethod - The method of notification (Write to File, Email, Display or None). This value is case-insensitive.
subject - A description of what the notification is about. 
destination - The destination of the notification (email address or filename). This field is required when notifyMethod is Email or Write to File.
notificationServer - The email server to send the notification through. This field is required when notifyMethod is Email.
from - The originator of the message (email "from" address).This field is required when notifyMethod is Email.
serverPort - The port the service to notify on the server is running on. This field used when notifyMethod is Email, and it is optional (it defaults to 25 if not specified).
htmlEmail - Default value is true. The value should be true if the email is in rich text/html format. The value should be false to send the email in plain text format.

Responses\:
success - The user was notified.
failure - Notification failed.

As mentioned above, some inputs are required for certain types of notification methods. In order to schedule a flow that in turn uses this flow, all of the required fields for the given notification method must be supplied, or else the flow will not be able to execute to completion. For example, if "notifyMethod" is "File", then the "destination" input must also be specified.

0e969447-37e3-4232-a012-c4e7fe7b1ea4.223b5bd8-f0e9-4c65-ab7d-d3f7dd34fbc7.description=Attempts to acquire the specified lock, and sleeps until the lock is available. 
Inputs\:
   lockId - the id of the lock, maximum 255 characters.
   timeout - The maximum number of seconds this flow will run for.
  seconds - The number of seconds to sleep for between each attempt at acquiring the lock.

Responses\:
   success - if the lock has been successfully acquired.
   failure - if the lock could not be acquired.

Result\:
   Code - 0 if the operation succeeds, 1 otherwise.

Notes\:
1) The locks acquired by this operation are not reentrant. This means that 
   once a lock is acquired by a run, all subsequent attempts at acquiring 
   the same lock by the same run (or any other run) will fail.

2) Once a run terminates, all the locks that were acquired during its execution
   are automatically released.

Synopsis

    This flow retrieves a list of LUNs based on the inputs received. Optional inputs restrict the search; if none are given, all LUNs are returned.
    getLuns performs the following steps\:
      1. Pass the flow inputs in and assign the optional argument variables for the configuration.
      2. Call the remote action server (RAS) perl with the inputs.
      3. Validate the XML document from the RAS results.
      4. Query the XML document for the results. If the code is invalid, encode the invalid XML and set the reason for failure based on the reason code (\= or not \= to 0).
      5. If the code is valid, query the results for a status. If the status is not passed, provide a reason for the error.
      6. Pass the information to the requesting entity.

Inputs

   clusterName - The IP or host name of the NetApp cluster; specifies endpoint to run the API against (required).     
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or RFC 1123 compliant host name.
      Default value\: None.

    vServerName - The name of the vServer used in the flow.
    path - The path to the command's executable file.
    mapped - Whether or not the LUN has a mapped path.
    online - Whether or not the LUN has an online (operational) status.
    serialNumber - The serial number of the LUN.
    osType - The type of operating system (OS).
    optArgVars- A query that specifies which  argument variables to return for the configuration (required).
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: None.

    overrideJRAS - Value to override the system-defined Java RAS server.
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: Hosting Eng RAS.

Results

    hpooFlowResult - The XML response specific to the functionality of the flow; in this case LUN information.
    flowStatus - Overall status of the flow, value is one of the string literals "success" or "failed".

Responses

    Success - All operations and subflows completed successfully.
    Failure - Some operations and/or subflows failed.
    Invalid XML document - The XML document returned in the response is not valid.

Notes

    1. Example output (eg inputs were clusterName and vServerName)\:

                        S223000SL7NAS01_root

                        5501853106179

0e969447-37e3-4232-a012-c4e7fe7b1ea4.4471790f-1c7b-424d-a148-07422e8ebe7b.description=
Synopsis

A high-level Unified Compute service that initiates LIF creation on a vServer; it handles calling runPlumbDataPathByProto and responding to the remote caller with a callback response.

    plumbVserverDataPath performs the following steps\:
      1. Acquire an exclusive lock, where the key is the vServer name.
      2. Check that the vServer exists.
      3. Call the HPOO flow runPlumbDataPathByProto to create the desired LIF.
      4. Do a callback to the calling entity, if applicable.

Inputs

    clusterName - The IP or host name of the NetApp cluster (required).
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or RFC 1123 compliant host name.
      Default value\: None.

    vServerName - The name of the vServer to be used in the flow. (required).
    protocol - The protocol, such as CIFS, NFS or FCP, that determines which underlying interface creation handler to execute (required).
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: None.

    ipAddress - The desired host IP address of the LIF (required for network LIF).
    netMask - The IP netmask for the host IP address (required for network LIF).
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address.
      Default value\: None.

    vlanId - The VLAN in the which the LIF resides (required for network LIF).
      Valid Values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: None.

    defaultGateway - IP address or hostname of the router that server as an access point other networks outside of the LIF's VLAN.
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or valid hostname.
      Default value\: None.

    node - A contoller node for the clusterName where the LIF should be created.
    port - The VLAN port which with the LIF is associated.
    interfaceName - The name of the LIF.
    routingGroup - A group of static routes associated with the LIF.
    parentInterface - The physical interface of the node where the LIF is created.
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: None.

    testMode - The test mode tells the flow whether the LIF retrieval is real (for provisioning) or a test for the process.
      Valid values\: Literal string "true" or "false" (case ignored).
      Default value\: False.

    VsLockTimeout - The maximum number of seconds to wait for a lock on this flow.
      Valid values\: Positive integer value.
      Default value\: 120 (2 minutes)

    VsLockSleep - The number of seconds to sleep for between each attempt at acquiring the lock.
      Valid values\: Positive integer value.
      Default value\: 0 (non-blocking)

    overrideJRAS - Value to override the system-defined Java RAS server.
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: Interpolated value of the hosteng_atlasras HPOO system property.

Results

    hpooFlowResult - The XML response specific to the functionality of the flow; returned in the HTTP POST operation envelope "hpooCallback". See Notes section for more details.
    flowStatus - Overall status of the flow, where the value is one of the string literals "success" or "failed".

Responses

    Success - All operations and subflows completed successfully.
    Failure - Some operations and/or subflows failed.

Notes

    1. The value and number of inputs is dependant on the type of LIF being created.
         a. For a network type LIF (NFS, CIFS, iSCSI), the minimal required inputs are all that is necessary. The underlying provisioning logic will determine the node/interface/port location for the LIF, as well as apply default naming for the associated vServer resources.
         b. For a SAN type LIF (FCP), the minimal required inputs are all that is necessary. The underlying provisioning logic will determine the node/interface/port location for the LIF, as well as apply default naming for the associated vServer resources.

Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

Synopsis

    This flow removes a map (or association) to an iGroup for an existing LUN. The association gives all the users of the iGroup access to the LUN. Optional inputs restrict the search, if none are given, all are returned.
    rmLunMap performs the following steps\:
      1. Pass the flow inputs in and assign the optional argument variables for the configuration.
      2. Call the remote action server (RAS) perl with the inputs to determine if a map exists that matches those inputs.
      3. Validate the XML document from the RAS results. This document contains the RAS results, and will either be a failure or success, depending on the results from the RAS.
      4. Query the XML document for the results. If the code is invalid, encode the invalid XML.
      5. If the code is valid, query the results for a status and determine that the status is passed. If it isn't passed, capture the reason for error.
      6. Pass the information to the requesting entity.

Inputs

    clusterName - The IP or host name of the NetApp cluster; specifies endpoint to run the API against (required).     
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or RFC 1123 compliant host name.
      Default value\: None.

    vServerName - The name of the vServer used in the flow (required).
    path - The path to the command's executable file (required).
    igroup - A collection of WWNs used to control access to a LUN (required).
    optArgVars- A query that specifies which  argument variables to return for the configuration (required).
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: None.

    overrideJRAS - Value to override the system-defined Java RAS server.
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: Hosting Eng RAS.

Results

    hpooFlowResult - The XML response specific to the functionality of the flow; in this case removing a LUN map to an iGroup.
    flowStatus - Overall status of the flow, value is one of the string literals "success" or "failed".

Responses

    Success - All operations and subflows completed successfully.
    Failure - Some operations and/or subflows failed.
    Invalid XML document - The XML document returned in the response is not valid.

Synopsis

A high-level Unified Compute service that initiates LIF creation on a vServer; it handles calling runPlumbDataPathByProto and responding to the remote caller with a callback response.

    plumbVserverDataPath performs the following steps\:
      1. Acquire an exclusive lock, where the key is the vServer name.
      2. Check that the vServer exists.
      3. Call the HPOO flow runPlumbDataPathByProto to create the desired LIF.
      4. Do a callback to the calling entity, if applicable.

Inputs

    clusterName - The IP or host name of the NetApp cluster (required).
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or RFC 1123 compliant host name.
      Default value\: None.

    vServerName - The name of the vServer to be used in the flow. (required).

Synopsis

    This flow creates an LUN using the specified inputs.
    buildLUN performs the following steps\:
      1. Set the volume parameters for iGroup, volume type, protocol, volume language, and volume size, and provisioning email destination.
      2. Obtain a lock on the vServer for provisioning.
      3. Determine if the flow is in test mode.
      4. Create a LUN.
      5. Retrieve the maximum size for a LUN.
      6. Retrieve valid iGroups.
      7. Determine if there are any iGroups found, and if so, if the operating system type matches the LUN.
      8. Run getSusSanVolNameAndLunPath to retrieve the volume name and LUN path.
      9. Calculate the maximum LUN size percentage.
    10. Calculate the and factorthe LUN size by bytes.
    11. Run createSusVolCommon to create the volume parameters.
    12. Run setSusLUNRwVolConfig to configure the volume type.
    13. Create a LUN by the size.
    14. Create a LUN map.
    15. Retrieve the LUN serial number.
    16. Build an XML payload of the volume name to pass to the requesting entity.
    17. Send an email with the flow results the specified email address.

    clusterName - The IP or host name of the NetApp cluster (required).
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or RFC 1123 compliant host name.
      Default value\: None.

    vServerName - The name of the vServer to be used in the flow (required).
    lunSize - The size of the LUN being provisioned (required).
    aggregateName - The NetApp aggregate name where the vServer's root volume is created (required).
    hostSeverName - The home or default server for the LUN.
    storageTier - The tier of storage (e.g. Vital, Velocity, or Value) (required).
    osType - The type of operating system (CIFS, NFS, etc.).
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.

    callerInstanceId - ID value of the caller to the HPOO web service.
    callbackEndpoint - URL to which the flow results should be posted (HTTP POST operation).
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: None.

    email destination - E-mail address for the recipient of the flow logging results (see the flowLogger flow variable).
      Valid values\: A valid e-mail address, e.g., bob.user@centurylink.com
      Default value\: None.

    testMode - The test mode tells the flow whether the LIF retrieval is real (for provisioning) or a test for the process.
      Valid values\: Literal string "true" or "false" (case ignored).
      Default value\: False.

      Valid values\: Positive integer value.

      Valid values\: Positive integer value.
      Default value\: 0 (non-blocking)

      Valid values\: Implementation specific.

Synopsis

    This flow retrieves a LUNs mapping configuration (for example, which data centers a LUN is assigned to). Optional inputs restrict the search; if none are given, all LUNs are returned.
    getLunMaps performs the following steps\:
      1. Pass the flow inputs in and assign the optional argument variables for the configuration.
      2. Call the remote action server (RAS) perl with the inputs.
      3. Validate the XML document from the RAS results.
      4. Query the XML document for the results. If the code is invalid, encode the invalid XML and set the reason for failure based on the reason code (\= or not \= to 0).
      5. If the code is valid, query the results for a status. If the status is not passed, provide a reason for the error.
      6. Pass the information to the requesting entity.

Inputs

   clusterName - The IP or host name of the NetApp cluster; specifies endpoint to run the API against (required).     
      Valid values\: Dot-decimal notation IPv4 address or RFC 1123 compliant host name.
      Default value\: None.

    vServerName - The name of the vServer used in the flow.
    path - The path to the command's executable file.
    igroup - A collection of WWNs used to control access to a LUN.
    igroupUuid - The unique identifying number for an iGroup.
    lunId - The identifying name for a LUN.
    lunUuid – The unique identifying number for a LUN.
    optArgVars- A query that specifies which  argument variables to return for the configuration (required).
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: None.

    overrideJRAS - Value to override the system-defined Java RAS server.
      Valid values\: Implementation-specific.
      Default value\: Hosting Eng RAS.
